ttle-raid Myths in Western Peloponnese / rNobili, Cecilia -- tTime and Space in Argolic Traditions: From Ocean to Europe / rPellizer, Ezio -- tAbout the Boeotian Origin of the Emmenidai's Genos: An Indication from Gela / rScirpo, Paolo Daniele -- tFighting on the River: The Alpheus and the 'Pylian Epic' / rZanetto, Giuseppe -- tTime and Space in the Myth of Byblis and Caunus / rVillagra, Nereida -- tMythological Time and Space in Ovid's Exile Poetry / rMichalopoulos, Andreas N. -- tPart IV. Shifting Chronotopes -- tKairos: The Appropriate Time, Place and Degree in Protagoras' Myth of Origins / rAndrews, James -- tFrom Here to Eternity: Mythologein in Plato's Phaedo / rZafiropoulos, Christos A. -- tOvid's Temple(s) of Vesta (Fasti 6.249- 460) / rGarani, Myrto -- tCarmenta in the Fasti: A Tale of Two Feasts / rPapaioannou, Sophia -- tThe Decisive Moment in Mythology: The Instant of Metamorphosis / rLétoublon, Françoise -- tIndex Locorum -- tIndex Nominum Notabiliorum -- tNotes on Contributors  aFrom Homer to Sophocles and Greek Middle Comedy, and from Plato and Protagoras to Ovid, this volume features a panoramic and cross-generic overview of the diverse handling and ad hoc elaboration of the overarching literary notions of "time" and "space". The twenty-one contributions of this volume written by an international group of esteemed scholars provide an equal number of hermeneutic approaches to individual, distinct aspects of Greek and Latin literature. The volume is purposely designed not as a linear display of knowledge, but rather as an anthology of select paradigms that aim to demonstrate the multidimensional function and multifaceted role of the twin notions of "time" and "space" throughout ancient Greek and Latin literary texts. The volume opens with analyses of conspicuous cases from epic poetry, proceeds with examples from drama (tragedy and comedy), and concludes with diverse instances of chronotopes (empirical, imaginary, and even shifting ones), in various literary genres. The volume is of greatest relevance since it meets the cultural and theoretical trends of today's Classics. It therefore will attract not only the interest of specialised Classicists but it is also intended for a wider general readership.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Mrz 2018) 4aAntike. 4aMythos. 4aRaum. 4aReligion. 4aTime. 4aZeit. 4aancient culture and literature. 4amyth. 4areligion. 4aspace.1 aBierl, Anton, eeditor.1 aChristopoulos, Menelaos, eeditor.1 aPapachrysostomou, Athina, eeditor.0 cEPUBz978-3-11-053422-10 cprintz978311053419140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110535150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110535150.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG